1
00:00:00,008 --> 00:00:01,725
In his left hand, a letter.

2
00:00:01,725 --> 00:00:03,493
Corday, Marat's murderer,

3
00:00:03,493 --> 00:00:04,527
did use a letter

4
00:00:04,527 --> 00:00:06,027
to get into the apartment,

5
00:00:06,027 --> 00:00:07,962
but this isn't that letter.

6
00:00:07,962 --> 00:00:10,396
David wrote those words himself.

7
00:00:10,396 --> 00:00:11,013
They make

8
00:00:11,013 --> 00:00:12,747
Marat look like a man killed

9
00:00:12,747 --> 00:00:14,648
while helping someone in need.

10
00:00:14,648 --> 00:00:16,048
David put it in his hand

11
00:00:16,048 --> 00:00:18,099
on purpose as part of the myth

12
00:00:18,099 --> 00:00:18,933
he was building.

13
00:00:18,933 --> 00:00:21,101
On the floor, the knife, bloodied,

14
00:00:21,101 --> 00:00:22,801
and on the wooden block

15
00:00:22,801 --> 00:00:23,885
besides the bath,

16
00:00:23,885 --> 00:00:26,370
the block Marat used as a desk,

17
00:00:26,370 --> 00:00:28,054
David carved 2 words.

18
00:00:28,054 --> 00:00:30,405
To Marat from David.

19
00:00:30,405 --> 00:00:33,340
He signed the painting into the painting.

20
00:00:33,340 --> 00:00:35,841
It's a dedication, a memorial,

21
00:00:35,841 --> 00:00:37,175
and a political act.

22
00:00:37,175 --> 00:00:38,725
Now, here's what I need you

23
00:00:38,725 --> 00:00:39,726
to sit with.

24
00:00:39,726 --> 00:00:42,544
This painting is propaganda.

25
00:00:42,544 --> 00:00:44,011
It absolutely is.

26
00:00:44,011 --> 00:00:45,312
David has taken a man

27
00:00:45,312 --> 00:00:48,580
who was, by many accounts, paranoid, cruel,

28
00:00:48,580 --> 00:00:51,448
and responsive for stirring up mob violence

29
00:00:51,448 --> 00:00:53,682
And turned him into a saint.

30
00:00:53,682 --> 00:00:57,117
The bath is clean, the body idealized.

31
00:00:57,117 --> 00:00:59,701
The composition is borrowed directly

32
00:00:59,701 --> 00:01:03,053
from Christian art, specifically the Pietà,

33
00:01:03,053 --> 00:01:04,387
which is a famous image

34
00:01:04,387 --> 00:01:06,938
of Mary holding the body of Jesus.

35
00:01:06,938 --> 00:01:09,923
You know this Michelangelo's famous sculpture?

36
00:01:09,923 --> 00:01:11,823
Do you see it?

37
00:01:11,823 --> 00:01:15,858
That arrangement, that specific quality of grief

38
00:01:15,858 --> 00:01:17,776
held perfectly still.

39
00:01:17,776 --> 00:01:21,478
David took it and transplanted it into a bathtub in Paris.

40
00:01:21,478 --> 00:01:25,013
Marat as the Revolution's crucified Christ.

41
00:01:25,013 --> 00:01:26,413
David made this painting

42
00:01:26,413 --> 00:01:27,664
to serve the revolution,

43
00:01:27,664 --> 00:01:28,814
to turn a murderer

44
00:01:28,814 --> 00:01:29,815
into a martyr,

45
00:01:29,815 --> 00:01:30,232
to make

46
00:01:30,232 --> 00:01:34,567
you feel something specific, grief, outrage, devotion

47
00:01:34,567 --> 00:01:35,267
to the cause.

48
00:01:35,267 --> 00:01:38,118
It's propaganda and it's a masterpiece.

49
00:01:38,118 --> 00:01:40,603
Both are true at the same time,

50
00:01:40,603 --> 00:01:42,320
and that tension

51
00:01:42,320 --> 00:01:44,521
is what makes David so important

52
00:01:44,521 --> 00:01:45,939
and so unsettling.

53
00:01:45,939 --> 00:01:51,975
He painted virtue. He preached sacrifice. And he signed the warrants that sent people to die.

54
00:01:51,975 --> 00:01:55,860
The revolution gave David everything: power, purpose,

55
00:01:55,860 --> 00:01:57,210
a reason to paint

56
00:01:57,210 --> 00:01:58,678
Now, it was about

57
00:01:58,678 --> 00:01:59,828
to take it all back.

58
00:01:59,828 --> 00:02:01,062
It couldn't last.

59
00:02:01,062 --> 00:02:03,513
The revolution, like all revolutions,

60
00:02:03,513 --> 00:02:05,147
started eating its own.

61
00:02:05,147 --> 00:02:08,932
On July 27th, 1794, Robespierre,

62
00:02:08,932 --> 00:02:13,351
the radical Jacobin leader, was overthrown, arrested,

63
00:02:13,351 --> 00:02:16,152
executed the next day, and soon

64
00:02:16,152 --> 00:02:18,120
after, they came for David.

65
00:02:18,120 --> 00:02:20,020
He was arrested, imprisoned.

66
00:02:20,020 --> 00:02:21,571
He came very close

67
00:02:21,571 --> 00:02:24,672
to the guillotine himself, the same guillotine

68
00:02:24,672 --> 00:02:26,790
he had helped send others to.

69
00:02:26,790 --> 00:02:29,375
His students lobbied for his release.

70
00:02:29,375 --> 00:02:30,825
It took months.

71
00:02:30,825 --> 00:02:33,493
And in prison, he did something remarkable.

72
00:02:33,493 --> 00:02:36,194
He painted himself not as a hero,

73
00:02:36,194 --> 00:02:37,562
not as a martyr,

74
00:02:37,562 --> 00:02:39,746
not as someone Roman or Greek,

75
00:02:39,746 --> 00:02:41,163
just himself.

76
00:02:41,163 --> 00:02:43,964
A middle-aged man with a swollen cheek.

77
00:02:43,964 --> 00:02:45,365
he had a facial tumor

78
00:02:45,365 --> 00:02:47,233
that distorted his features.

79
00:02:47,233 --> 00:02:49,517
Holding a palette, looking out at you

80
00:02:49,517 --> 00:02:52,135
with an expression that's hard to read.

81
00:02:52,135 --> 00:02:53,302
Surprise?

82
00:02:53,302 --> 00:02:54,603
Confusion?

83
00:02:54,603 --> 00:02:55,553
Honesty?

84
00:02:55,553 --> 00:02:57,854
It might be the most intimate thing

85
00:02:57,854 --> 00:02:59,071
he ever painted

86
00:02:59,071 --> 00:03:01,456
because it wasn't for anyone.

87
00:03:01,456 --> 00:03:03,140
It wasn't for the salon

88
00:03:03,140 --> 00:03:04,657
or for the revolution.

89
00:03:04,657 --> 00:03:06,241
It was just a man

90
00:03:06,241 --> 00:03:08,659
in a cell looking at himself.

91
00:03:08,659 --> 00:03:09,576
And don't ask me

92
00:03:09,576 --> 00:03:12,410
how he got painting materials in prison.

93
00:03:12,410 --> 00:03:13,544
After his release,

94
00:03:13,544 --> 00:03:15,128
he said he had been deceived

95
00:03:15,128 --> 00:03:17,113
by the mask of patriotism.

96
00:03:17,113 --> 00:03:18,346
Was he?

97
00:03:18,346 --> 00:03:19,964
Was he really deceived,

98
00:03:19,964 --> 00:03:21,565
or was he just saying

99
00:03:21,565 --> 00:03:23,715
what he needed to say to survive?

100
00:03:23,715 --> 00:03:26,450
That's one of the great unanswerable questions

101
00:03:26,450 --> 00:03:28,901
about David, and I think

102
00:03:28,901 --> 00:03:30,402
the answer might be both.

103
00:03:30,402 --> 00:03:31,819
He was a true believer

104
00:03:31,819 --> 00:03:34,254
who was also very good in surviving.

105
00:03:34,254 --> 00:03:35,788
People are complicated.

106
00:03:35,788 --> 00:03:37,838
And then he met Napoleon.

107
00:03:37,838 --> 00:03:39,489
It was 1797.

108
00:03:39,489 --> 00:03:42,557
Napoleon was a young general, already famous,

109
00:03:42,557 --> 00:03:45,275
already radiating that kind of charisma

110
00:03:45,275 --> 00:03:47,826
that makes painter reach for their brushes.

111
00:03:47,826 --> 00:03:49,560
David met him and wrote,

112
00:03:49,560 --> 00:03:50,477
Oh, my friends,

113
00:03:50,477 --> 00:03:52,128
what a beautiful head he has.

114
00:03:52,128 --> 00:03:54,012
It is pure, it is great.

115
00:03:54,012 --> 00:03:56,247
It is as beautiful as the antique.

116
00:03:56,247 --> 00:03:57,914
As beautiful as the antique.

117
00:03:57,914 --> 00:03:59,198
There it is again.

118
00:03:59,198 --> 00:04:01,616
David looked at a living, breathing military

119
00:04:01,616 --> 00:04:04,284
commander and saw a Greek statue.

120
00:04:04,284 --> 00:04:05,484
He couldn't help himself.

121
00:04:05,484 --> 00:04:07,735
And Napoleon, a master of image

122
00:04:07,735 --> 00:04:09,836
and spectacle, saw in David

123
00:04:09,836 --> 00:04:11,620
exactly what he needed.

124
00:04:11,620 --> 00:04:14,255
The greatest painter of his time, ready

125
00:04:14,255 --> 00:04:16,572
to turn him into a living legend.

126
00:04:16,572 --> 00:04:19,657
Okay.Napoleon crossing the Alps, 1801.

127
00:04:19,657 --> 00:04:21,425
You know this image.

128
00:04:21,425 --> 00:04:22,242
Even if

129
00:04:22,242 --> 00:04:24,726
you never been into an art museum,

130
00:04:24,726 --> 00:04:26,377
you know this image.

131
00:04:26,377 --> 00:04:27,744
Napoleon on a rearing

132
00:04:27,744 --> 00:04:30,745
white horse, cape flowing, arm pointing

133
00:04:30,745 --> 00:04:34,314
forward, the names of Hannibal and Charlemagne

134
00:04:34,314 --> 00:04:36,248
carved into the rocks below him,

135
00:04:36,248 --> 00:04:37,232
As if to say

136
00:04:37,232 --> 00:04:38,932
he belongs among them.

137
00:04:38,932 --> 00:04:40,766
I've seen this painting in person,

138
00:04:40,766 --> 00:04:42,000
and the first thing

139
00:04:42,000 --> 00:04:43,601
that hits you is the scale.

140
00:04:43,601 --> 00:04:45,002
If you see it on a screen,

141
00:04:45,002 --> 00:04:47,770
it's completely different from how

142
00:04:47,770 --> 00:04:49,937
people back at the time felt when

143
00:04:49,937 --> 00:04:52,188
they saw it in front of them.

144
00:04:52,188 --> 00:04:55,256
Like, this painting is about this size,

145
00:04:55,256 --> 00:04:55,940
you just stand

146
00:04:55,940 --> 00:04:57,757
in front of it, and you feel

147
00:04:57,757 --> 00:04:59,658
that you're looking at something amazing.

148
00:04:59,658 --> 00:05:00,809
I can't explain it.

149
00:05:00,809 --> 00:05:02,276
You, you have to experience it,

150
00:05:02,276 --> 00:05:04,244
'cause I was really surprised

151
00:05:04,244 --> 00:05:05,144
to feel that way.

152
00:05:05,144 --> 00:05:06,561
Okay, back to the story.

153
00:05:06,561 --> 00:05:08,045
The painting is huge.

154
00:05:08,045 --> 00:05:09,863
You stand in front of it, and

155
00:05:09,863 --> 00:05:12,297
you feel small, which is, of course,

156
00:05:12,297 --> 00:05:13,498
exactly the point.

157
00:05:13,498 --> 00:05:13,998
Napoleon

158
00:05:13,998 --> 00:05:15,865
asked to be painted calm

159
00:05:15,865 --> 00:05:17,316
on a spirited horse.

160
00:05:17,316 --> 00:05:18,717
David delivered.

161
00:05:18,717 --> 00:05:19,867
Here's the thing, though.

162
00:05:19,867 --> 00:05:22,502
The real crossing was difficult, cold,

163
00:05:22,502 --> 00:05:24,286
and unglamorous.

164
00:05:24,286 --> 00:05:26,470
Napoleon rode a mule for much

165
00:05:26,470 --> 00:05:28,521
of it, led by a local guide.

166
00:05:28,521 --> 00:05:31,039
David wasn't painting what happened.

167
00:05:31,039 --> 00:05:31,889
He was painting

168
00:05:31,889 --> 00:05:34,941
what Napoleon wanted to believe about himself.

169
00:05:34,941 --> 00:05:36,591
The heroic version.

170
00:05:36,591 --> 00:05:37,175
The myth.

171
00:05:37,175 --> 00:05:39,009
Nobody remembers the mule.

172
00:05:39,009 --> 00:05:40,893
Everyone remembers this.

173
00:05:40,893 --> 00:05:42,611
And then there's the coronation.

174
00:05:42,611 --> 00:05:45,012
1805 to 1807.

175
00:05:45,012 --> 00:05:47,129
Over 30 feet wide.

176
00:05:47,129 --> 00:05:50,498
Napoleon crowning Josephine at Notre Dame,

177
00:05:50,498 --> 00:05:52,782
surrounded by hundreds of figures.

178
00:05:52,782 --> 00:05:54,416
David was there in person,

179
00:05:54,416 --> 00:05:55,633
sketching the ceremony.

180
00:05:55,633 --> 00:05:57,884
But he rearranged reality.

181
00:05:57,884 --> 00:06:00,802
Look, see that woman in the balcony?

182
00:06:00,802 --> 00:06:03,437
That's Napoleon's mother, Leticia.

183
00:06:03,437 --> 00:06:07,072
She's prominently placed, watching proudly.

184
00:06:07,072 --> 00:06:09,756
Except she wasn't there.

185
00:06:09,756 --> 00:06:11,357
She refused to come.

186
00:06:11,357 --> 00:06:13,741
David painted her in anyway

187
00:06:13,741 --> 00:06:16,076
because Napoleon wanted her there.

188
00:06:16,076 --> 00:06:17,743
The painting isn't a record

189
00:06:17,743 --> 00:06:18,994
of what happened.

190
00:06:18,994 --> 00:06:19,944
It's a record

191
00:06:19,944 --> 00:06:21,795
of what should have happened

192
00:06:21,795 --> 00:06:23,446
According to the man in charge.

193
00:06:23,446 --> 00:06:26,497
After Napoleon's final defeat in 1815,

194
00:06:26,497 --> 00:06:28,715
the Bourbon monarchy was restored, and

195
00:06:28,715 --> 00:06:30,732
they had a long memory.

196
00:06:30,732 --> 00:06:33,067
David had voted to execute their king

197
00:06:33,067 --> 00:06:34,617
in 1793.

198
00:06:34,617 --> 00:06:37,035
That was 22 years ago.

199
00:06:37,035 --> 00:06:38,636
They hadn't forgotten.

200
00:06:38,636 --> 00:06:40,770
He was exiled, banned from France

201
00:06:40,770 --> 00:06:41,870
as a king killer.

202
00:06:41,870 --> 00:06:44,272
He moved to Brussels and kept painting,

203
00:06:44,272 --> 00:06:47,456
but the work got softer, less urgent.

204
00:06:47,456 --> 00:06:49,107
The fire was going out.

205
00:06:49,107 --> 00:06:50,158
He died in Brussels

206
00:06:50,158 --> 00:06:52,975
on December 29th, 1825,

207
00:06:52,975 --> 00:06:54,693
at the age of 77.

208
00:06:54,693 --> 00:06:55,560
France refused

209
00:06:55,560 --> 00:06:57,177
to allow his body to return.

210
00:06:57,177 --> 00:06:58,044
The man who had

211
00:06:58,044 --> 00:06:59,778
been the most powerful artist

212
00:06:59,778 --> 00:07:00,829
in the country,

213
00:07:00,829 --> 00:07:02,847
who had shaped the visual identity

214
00:07:02,847 --> 00:07:04,931
of the revolution, of Napoleon,

215
00:07:04,931 --> 00:07:06,582
of an entire era,

216
00:07:06,582 --> 00:07:08,732
was buried in a foreign city.

217
00:07:08,732 --> 00:07:09,983
He's still there.

218
00:07:09,983 --> 00:07:11,017
So, what did

219
00:07:11,017 --> 00:07:12,417
David leave behind?

220
00:07:12,417 --> 00:07:15,369
A movement, a set of rules,

221
00:07:15,369 --> 00:07:18,003
and an institution, the Académie Royale,

222
00:07:18,003 --> 00:07:20,021
that would enforce those rules

223
00:07:20,021 --> 00:07:21,988
for the next 50 years.

224
00:07:21,988 --> 00:07:23,622
His greatest student, Ingres,

225
00:07:23,622 --> 00:07:26,174
became the guardian of that legacy.

226
00:07:26,174 --> 00:07:28,108
He spent his entire career

227
00:07:28,108 --> 00:07:31,609
defending classical drawing, insisting that discipline

228
00:07:31,609 --> 00:07:34,361
and line were the foundation of everything.

229
00:07:34,361 --> 00:07:35,911
The Académie backed him.

230
00:07:35,911 --> 00:07:38,362
For decades, the world David built held.

231
00:07:38,362 --> 00:07:39,413
So here's

232
00:07:39,413 --> 00:07:40,730
where I want to leave you.

233
00:07:40,730 --> 00:07:44,265
David understood something fundamental about images.

234
00:07:44,265 --> 00:07:47,500
They aren't just decoration, they're arguments.

235
00:07:47,500 --> 00:07:49,801
A painting can make you believe something.

236
00:07:49,801 --> 00:07:50,985
It can make an idea

237
00:07:50,985 --> 00:07:53,853
feel noble, inevitable, even heroic.

238
00:07:53,853 --> 00:07:54,503
his style

239
00:07:54,503 --> 00:07:56,754
helped make that power possible

240
00:07:56,754 --> 00:07:59,672
The clean lines, the stark compositions,

241
00:07:59,672 --> 00:08:02,056
the restrained, controlled color.

242
00:08:02,056 --> 00:08:05,391
Everything is clear, deliberate, and serious.

243
00:08:05,391 --> 00:08:07,192
Nothing is accidental.

244
00:08:07,192 --> 00:08:09,276
The paintings feel certain

245
00:08:09,276 --> 00:08:10,760
about what they are saying,

246
00:08:10,760 --> 00:08:13,161
and that certainty is persuasive.

247
00:08:13,161 --> 00:08:15,746
And the images themself did real work.

248
00:08:15,746 --> 00:08:17,430
The Oath of the Horatii

249
00:08:17,430 --> 00:08:19,447
didn't just show Roman virtue,

250
00:08:19,447 --> 00:08:20,881
it presented a model

251
00:08:20,881 --> 00:08:22,749
of duty and sacrifice.

252
00:08:22,749 --> 00:08:25,167
The Death of Marat didn't simply show

253
00:08:25,167 --> 00:08:27,568
a political killing, it transformed Marat

254
00:08:27,568 --> 00:08:29,368
into a martyr of the revolution.

255
00:08:29,368 --> 00:08:30,919
Napoleon crossing the Alps

256
00:08:30,919 --> 00:08:35,571
didn't document an event. It constructed Napoleon's image of leadership.

257
00:08:35,571 --> 00:08:45,209
That’s David’s real legacy. Not just a style, and not only a school of followers but a demonstration of how powerful images can shape political imagination.

258
00:08:45,209 --> 00:08:46,910
But the more interesting part

259
00:08:46,910 --> 00:08:49,177
of David's story isn't the propaganda,

260
00:08:49,177 --> 00:08:50,695
it's the man behind it.

261
00:08:50,695 --> 00:08:53,846
David painted virtue, duty, and sacrifice,

262
00:08:53,846 --> 00:08:56,464
and he seemed to have genuinely believe

263
00:08:56,464 --> 00:08:57,814
in those ideals.

264
00:08:57,814 --> 00:08:59,198
At the same time,

265
00:08:59,198 --> 00:09:01,233
he lived at the center of power

266
00:09:01,233 --> 00:09:03,384
during one of the most violent

267
00:09:03,384 --> 00:09:05,768
and chaotic periods in French history.

268
00:09:05,768 --> 00:09:07,569
That combination was rare.

269
00:09:07,569 --> 00:09:10,437
An artist who wasn't just observing events,

270
00:09:10,437 --> 00:09:12,221
but helping shape how

271
00:09:12,221 --> 00:09:13,738
they were seen and remembered.

272
00:09:13,738 --> 00:09:14,789
And that may be

273
00:09:14,789 --> 00:09:16,923
what makes him so remarkable.

274
00:09:16,923 --> 00:09:18,640
Not just a great painter,

275
00:09:18,640 --> 00:09:19,858
but an artist

276
00:09:19,858 --> 00:09:22,292
whose images helped define an era.

277
00:09:22,292 --> 00:09:23,859
But not everyone accepted

278
00:09:23,859 --> 00:09:25,243
what David had built

279
00:09:25,243 --> 00:09:27,511
Not everyone thought paintings

280
00:09:27,511 --> 00:09:29,212
should be lessons in virtue

281
00:09:29,212 --> 00:09:31,496
or that reason should rule everything art

282
00:09:31,496 --> 00:09:31,930
could be.

283
00:09:31,930 --> 00:09:34,748
